EvenUp × OpenClaw Hackathon — Scoring

Mission. Build a legal reserach agent that helps a personal injury attorney do their job — ingest legal data, organize it into a workflow, and chase down the data they don't have.


What everyone builds: the Harvester (required)

Every team ships a queryable database of California motor vehicle statutes — the CA Vehicle Code as the baseline. Real source URLs, a documented schema, working queries.

This isn't a data-dumping exercise. We expect you to research how attorneys actually use this data, design your schema deliberately, and ship a query interface a non-engineer could use. Thoughtful data design is half the score on this layer. 

Going deeper here scores more points:
- More US jurisdictions — vehicle codes from other states beyond California. This is exactly what the held-out eval tests, so this is the highest-leverage place to invest.
- Related regulations and case law interpreting key sections
- Authoritative websites — bar associations, court websites, plaintiff firm publications, government agencies. Bonus for building a curated wiki of which online sources are authoritative for what.
- Federal datasets — NHTSA / CDC / OSHA accident and injury data
- Smarter modeling of relationships between statutes, regulations, and cases


Evaluation: released set + held-out set

Released at kickoff (eval-ca-vehicle-code.csv). 41 California Vehicle Code statutes, each labeled with a contributing factor across 17 categories — DUI, failure to yield, improper passing, reckless driving, and so on. Some categories have multiple example statutes; a third only have one. Every statute in the released set should be in your Harvester at judging time.

Use the released set however helps you build: train on it, design tags around the labels, ignore them. Note the thin tail — categories with only one labeled example are where memorization breaks and real semantic modeling earns its keep.

Held out, revealed at judging. A broader, multi-state set of statutes labeled with the same contributing-factor schema. We don't release it. At judging we run live queries against your Harvester from the held-out set — citation lookup and contributing-factor retrieval. This is the real test: California-only systems score the floor; teams that ingested more jurisdictions and modeled the schema generalizably will score the ceiling. Hardcoded answers won't help — the live demo verifies real retrieval.


What you build on top (optional, encouraged)

Pick what excites you. Depth beats breadth — going hard on one extension beats a shallow attempt at both.

The Organizer
A research workspace a paralegal would actually use. Tag PI-relevant statutes and case law, surface coverage gaps, make damages comparables sortable. 

The Negotiator
An agent that spots a paywalled gap, finds the data holder, drafts outreach, and tracks the pipeline. Real publishers and verifiable contacts only. 


How we score (out of 100)

Harvester (50) — required
Half on data design — schema, query interface, how well a non-engineer can actually get answers out of it. Half on coverage — measured against both the released CA set (floor) and the held-out multi-state set (ceiling). More jurisdictions, regulations, case law, and authoritative web sources all push you toward the ceiling.

What you built on top (30)
How well your Organizer or Negotiator (or both) actually solves an attorney's problem. Stacking is fine, but a deep single extension beats two shallow ones.

Craft (10)
Clean code, thoughtful UX, sensible architecture. The kind of project you'd be proud to show in an interview.

Story (10)
A 5-minute demo that makes us believe in it.

Ground rules
- Source everything. Records without a real source URL don't count.
- No fabricated publishers or contacts in outreach drafts.
- Be ready to demo live on a query the judges pick — no hardcoded answers.


